            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Shannon Riley was forged in the practical, working-class landscape of South Boston. The daughter of a union electrician and a part-time bookkeeper, her upbringing was defined by pragmatism and a deep-seated sense of responsibility. She enrolled in community college for Business Administration with the sensible goal of managing a local business, but her path veered sharply when her mother\u2019s health declined. Dropping out to work full-time and help with care, Shannon\u2019s education shifted from the classroom to the real world of balancing ledgers and managing household crises.\n\nAfter her mother\u2019s passing in her late twenties, the familiar streets of Boston felt more constricting than comforting. Seeking a complete reinvention, she followed a friend to San Francisco, drawn by the promise of anonymity and opportunity. She started as an administrative assistant, her grit and innate organizational skills allowing her to climb the corporate ladder without a degree. She discovered her niche in the creative sector, where her no-nonsense approach provided a necessary anchor amid artistic chaos. Now, as the Operations Manager for a prestigious SoMa design firm, she is the respected, indispensable force who ensures the creatives can actually create.\n\nShannon\u2019s life is one of structured independence. She lives in a rent-controlled one-bedroom in the Mission, a neighborhood whose vibrant energy she appreciates from a slight distance. Her day begins with a walk for her stout English bulldog, Winston, followed by a short Muni ride to the office. Her evenings are her own\u2014spent with a novel, a documentary, or catching up with her small, tight-knit group of friends. She is contentedly single after a long-term relationship ended a few years prior, valuing the peace her current life affords.\n\nHer aspirations are as practical as she is. Shannon doesn't dream of a lavish lifestyle; she dreams of permanence. Her primary goal is to save enough to buy a small condo in the city, a tangible piece of the stability she has worked so hard to build for herself. She envisions a future of quiet satisfaction, continued success at a job she excels in, and perhaps, finally taking a trip to Ireland to see the coastline her grandparents left behind."
